                                                                <comments>
                            <comment id="18142" author="andypiper" created="Wed, 21 Jun 2006 03:43:19 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Patch that fixes the issue for me.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="18399" author="juergen.hoeller" created="Wed, 5 Jul 2006 00:41:30 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve addressed this (and another issue - inheriting the ClassLoader from a parent ApplicationContext) through the introduction of a &quot;getClassLoader()&quot; method on our ResourceLoader interface. This was straightforward enough to do, since all ResourceLoader implementations already expose a public &quot;getClassLoader()&quot; method anyway - just wasn&apos;t in the interface before. This avoids the need to pass a ClassLoader through to the ResourceEntityResolver, which simply uses the ClassLoader of the given ResourceLoader now.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This does raise the issue of custom ResourceLoader implementations having to expose a &quot;getClassLoader()&quot; method now. However, this is a minor issue since there won&apos;t be many custom ResourceLoader impls (that don&apos;t derive from DefaultResourceLoader), and it&apos;s easy enough to upgrade those. Such custom ResourceLoader impls will even still be backwards-compatible with Spring 1.2, since the new method doesn&apos;t hurt there (which is potentially important for third-party libraries that want to work with both Spring 1.2 and 2.0).&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Juergen&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
